    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - 5 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS SPICER ES70-5 - DISASSEMBLE - CASE
        AND CLUTCH HOUSING
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="14">
        <title>CASE AND CLUTCH HOUSING</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1301109">Figure 9</hotlnk>.
        </para>
        <figure id="f1301109" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1301109" filename="../figg13/g1301109.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 9. Case and Clutch Housing Exploded View</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. CASE</callout1>
                <callout1>2. REAR BEARING CAP</callout1>
                <callout1>3. BOLT</callout1>
                <callout1>4. LIFT HOOK</callout1>
                <callout1>5. FRONT BEARING CAP</callout1>
                <callout1>6. GASKET</callout1>
                <callout1>7. FILLER PLUG</callout1>
                <callout1>8. DRAIN PLUG</callout1>
                <callout1>9. PTO OPENING COVER</callout1>
                <callout1>10. ZERK</callout1>
                <callout1>11. BUSHING</callout1>
                <callout1>12. COVER</callout1>
                <callout1>13. CLUTCH HOUSING</callout1>
                <callout1>14. OIL SEAL</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Begin disassembly by removing the shifter housing and gasket (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301110">Figure 10</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301110" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301110" filename="../figg13/g1301110.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 10. Remove Shifter Housing and Gasket</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the springs and poppet balls from the shifter housing so you don't lose them. Then
                remove the shifter housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301111">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301111" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301111" filename="../figg13/g1301111.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 11. Remove Shifter Housing</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the input bearing cap bolts. Place two of the bolts in the threaded holes in the
                bearing cap. Tighten them to separate the cap from the housing. Also remove the bearing cap gasket and
                input shaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301112">Figure 12</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301112" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301112" filename="../figg13/g1301112.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 12. Remove Bearing Cap Gasket</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Replace the seal with a new one (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301113">Figure 13</hotlnk>). Inspect the bearing cup for damage. Replace if necessary.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301113" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301113" filename="../figg13/g1301113.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 13. Inspect Bearing Cup</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the end yoke (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301114">Figure 14</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301114" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301114" filename="../figg13/g1301114.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 14. Remove End Yoke</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the rear bearing cap, bearing race, gasket and speedometer gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301115">Figure 15</hotlnk>). Tightening 3/8 inch bolts in the special holes will help
                separate the cap from the transmission case. Note that mainshaft endplay is adjustable through a spacer
                and shims in this rear bearing cap.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301115" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301115" filename="../figg13/g1301115.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 15. Remove Rear Bearing Cap</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a chain hoist to lift the mainshaft from the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301116">Figure 16</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301116" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301116" filename="../figg13/g1301116.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 16. Lift Mainshaft From Case</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the clutch housing bolts (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301117">Figure 17</hotlnk>). Remove the clutch housing. It may be helpful to tap the
                clutch housing with a rubber mallet to loosen it from the case.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301117" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301117" filename="../figg13/g1301117.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 17. Remove Clutch Housing Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the countershaft lubrication spacer from the case bore (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301118">Figure 18</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301118" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301118" filename="../figg13/g1301118.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 18. Countershaft Lubrication Spacer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the countershaft rear bearing cap, shims, and bearing cup (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301119">Figure 19</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301119" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301119" filename="../figg13/g1301119.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 19. Countershaft Rear Bearing Cap</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The reverse idler shaft may be removed (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301120">Figure 20</hotlnk>). Puller ZTSE-4324 is recommended. Refer to
                <hotlnk document="s13011_35.xml" xrefid="f1301168">SPECIAL TOOLS</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301120" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301120" filename="../figg13/g1301120.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 20. Reverse Idler Shaft</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lift the reverse idler gear and thrust washers out of the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301121">Figure 21</hotlnk>). The idler gear contains two bearings and a spacer in its
                bore. Inspect them and replace if worn or damaged.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301121" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301121" filename="../figg13/g1301121.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Reverse Idler Gear and Thrust Washers</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a chain hoist to remove the countershaft from the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301122">Figure 22</hotlnk>). The input bearing race can be removed now. Inspect and
                clean all reusable parts.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301122" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301122" filename="../figg13/g1301122.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Remove Countershaft From Case</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
